{"key":"processedPost-9511548","value":{"id":9511548,"first":9511190,"last":9512190,"when":1230569518,"utime":"12/29/08 06:51 PM","content":"A common misconception is that a substrate will only pin where light hits it.&nbsp; Such is not the case.&nbsp; The mycelium is a single organism, therefore light on top of the substrate can initiate pinning on the bottom, if conditions are better for fruiting down there.&nbsp; It doesn't matter how well you block the light.<br /><br />Perhaps fresh air(not CO2) is finding a way to the bottom.&nbsp; If all transpiration occurs on top, that's where the pins will form.&nbsp; Fresh air is a much more important pinning trigger than light, which is a secondary trigger.<br />RR","title":"Re: Normally I'd love this sight, but... DAMN!","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}